result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

The disposition of "Other" is used to indicate several different dispositions. The Charge(s)/Sentence(s) and Court Record Events sections of the WCCA record display additional information that must be reviewed in order to determine the exact disposition of the charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Motion hearing on November 4, 2016 at 10:30 am.

Defendant Lindsay N Hauser in court.  Jodie L. Bednar appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 10:16 AM. State puts on record the reason for the filing of the motion to revoke the DPA. Court asks some questions regarding what was plead to and if the defendant is currently on probation. State responds. Hauser wants counsel, did talk to her counsel and she was scheduled to be here but Ms. Burns had an emergency and was out of town until tomorrow. State would like to contact SPD to see if the defendant indeed called SPD two weeks ago like she justed indicated on the record. Court calls SPD - off the record. Court questions the secretary  in regards to talking to the defendant recently, off record. Court not taking up this matter today as the defendant has indicated that she wants counsel. Court sets for motion hearing with Court, State, defense counsel and State's witness appearing in person in Oneida County and defendant can appear telephonically from Madison, Court reminds that any documents that will be used in the motion to be exchanged with counsel within the next 10 days.  Motion hearing scheduled for November 4, 2016 at 10:30 am.
